		"ITEM_DESCRIPTION" : "<div data-bbid=\"bbml-editor-id_6f76eb29-5184-47f2-9a2b-26f9518edb98\"><p>In still photography, the typical method of professional lighting is most commonly known as three-point lighting. This technique entails setting up three different lights in three distinct positions. By adjusting the size, distance, intensity, and positioning of these lights, the photographer can control the interplay of light and shadow on the subject, thus creating diverse atmospheric nuances.<\/p><p><a href=\"@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav\/xid-18265298_1\" data-bbtype=\"attachment\" data-bbfile=\"{&quot;alternativeText&quot;:&quot;8th+Street+Studios+&quot;,&quot;displayName&quot;:&quot;8th+Street+Studios+&quot;,&quot;fileName&quot;:&quot;8th+Street+Studios+-+Equipment.jpg&quot;,&quot;fileSize&quot;:462877,&quot;isDecorative&quot;:true,&quot;mimeType&quot;:&quot;image\/jpeg&quot;,&quot;render&quot;:&quot;inlineOnly&quot;,&quot;resourceUrl&quot;:&quot;@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@sessions\/4F\/4FAF415557620BCB6BDF74D31D4A47F0\/860ddd0cfaa04074ac041d42ff8250bb\/8th%2BStreet%2BStudios%2B-%2BEquipment.jpg&quot;,&quot;linkName&quot;:&quot;8th+Street+Studios+&quot;}\">8th+Street+Studios+<\/a><\/p><pre>&nbsp;<\/pre><br><h4><span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">What is Three-Point Lighting?<\/span><\/h4><br><p><span style=\"color: #000000\">Three-point lighting is a fundamental lighting technique used in photography, and even film production, that allows you to manipulate the illumination of your subject to achieve your desired visual outcome.&nbsp;It involves using three key light sources placed in specific positions relative to the subject:<\/span><\/p><p><a href=\"@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav\/xid-18265264_1\" data-bbtype=\"attachment\" data-bbfile=\"{&quot;alternativeText&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;displayName&quot;:&quot;Slide 16_9 - 3.png&quot;,&quot;fileName&quot;:&quot;Slide 16_9 - 3.png&quot;,&quot;fileSize&quot;:1209273,&quot;isDecorative&quot;:true,&quot;mimeType&quot;:&quot;image\/png&quot;,&quot;render&quot;:&quot;inlineOnly&quot;,&quot;resourceUrl&quot;:&quot;@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@sessions\/4F\/4FAF415557620BCB6BDF74D31D4A47F0\/3ada9a4a817d4702a1d14ed5a0d0f7b0\/Slide%2016_9%20-%203.png&quot;,&quot;linkName&quot;:&quot;Slide 16_9 - 3.png&quot;}\">Slide 16_9 - 3.png<\/a><\/p><p><span style=\"color: var(--tw-prose-bold)\"><strong>Key Light&nbsp;<\/strong><\/span><span style=\"color: var(--tw-prose-bold)\">-&nbsp;<\/span>This is the main and usually the strongest light source. It is positioned at a higher angle and shines directly on the subject, creating highlights and defining the subject's shape. The key light is the primary source that sets the tone for the lighting setup.<\/p><p><span style=\"color: var(--tw-prose-bold)\"><strong>Rim Light&nbsp;<\/strong><\/span>- The rim light, otherwise known as the hair or back light, is positioned behind the subject, aiming toward the subject's back. It helps separate the subject from the background by creating a rim of light around the subject's edges. This adds depth and dimension to the image and prevents the subject from blending into the background.<\/p><p><span style=\"color: var(--tw-prose-bold)\"><strong>Fill Light&nbsp;<\/strong><\/span><span style=\"color: var(--tw-prose-bold)\">- T<\/span>he fill light is placed on the opposite side of the key light. Its purpose is to soften the shadows created by the key light, providing a more even and balanced illumination. The intensity of the fill light is often lower than that of the key light.<\/p><p>By adjusting the intensity, angle, and distance of these three light sources, photographers can control the distribution of light and shadow on the subject, as well as the overall mood and visual impact of the scene.&nbsp;<\/p><p>This technique allows for versatility in creating various lighting styles, from dramatic and high-contrast, to soft and well-lit, depending on the desired aesthetic and storytelling goals of the photographer.<\/p><\/div>",
