		"ITEM_DESCRIPTION" : "<div data-bbid=\"bbml-editor-id_d6820231-31df-4376-a6d4-8bdde358a638\"><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000\">Photographers often employ an array of compositional elements to enhance their images and boost their visual appeal. These include elements like patterns, textures, lines, shapes, forms, and more. Think of it as like a photographer's toolbox! Now, if you're curious to learn more about what makes a photo look great, keep reading on as we explore the five essential building blocks of photography composition.<\/span><\/p><h6 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"color: #000000\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/h6><pre>&nbsp;<\/pre><h6><strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/h6><h4><strong>1. Shape<\/strong><\/h4><h6>&nbsp;<\/h6><p><span style=\"color: #000000\">Shape serves as a two-dimensional compositional element in photography, capable of defining subjects or structures within an image. These shapes can take on an organic quality, representing living beings or natural elements, or they can adopt a more geometric nature, embodying forms like squares, circles, or triangles. Moreover, when various shapes intersect or overlap, they can combine to form entirely new shapes, or they can enclose a space, thereby creating additional shapes within the composition.<\/span><\/p><p><img src=\"https:\/\/blog.depositphotos.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/12\/Photo-composition-element-shape.jpg.webp\" alt=\"photo composition element shape\"><span style=\"color: #666666\"><span style=\"font-size: 0.625rem;\">Image source: Bob Books UK<\/span><\/span><\/p><pre>&nbsp;<\/pre><h6>&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/h6><h4><span style=\"color: #000000\"><strong>2. Form<\/strong><\/span><\/h4><h6>&nbsp;<\/h6><p><span style=\"color: #000000\">Form is created when a shape becomes three-dimensional. This is achieved by introducing depth to a photograph through the interplay of lighting and perspective. Consequently, as shapes interact with shadows, we see the contours of a subject come to life, accentuated by variations in tonal range.<\/span><\/p><p><img src=\"https:\/\/blog.depositphotos.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/12\/Photo-composition-element-form.jpg.webp\" alt=\"photo composition element form\"><span style=\"color: #666666\"><span style=\"font-size: 0.625rem;\">Image source: Bob Books UK<\/span><\/span><\/p><pre>&nbsp;<\/pre><h6><strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/h6><h4><span style=\"color: #000000\"><strong>3. Texture<\/strong><\/span><\/h4><h6>&nbsp;<\/h6><p><span style=\"color: #000000\">Texture is a compositional element of photography that enhances an image by introducing an additional layer of realism and tangibility. Texture can either be the primary focus of a photograph, as seen in subjects like rough surfaces or intricate leaf patterns, or it can become an integral component of the composition itself, adding dimension to your image and giving it a sense of reality (refer to the image below).<\/span><\/p><p><img src=\"https:\/\/blog.depositphotos.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/12\/Photo-composition-element-texture.jpg.webp\" alt=\"photo composition element texture\"><span style=\"color: #666666\"><span style=\"font-size: 0.625rem;\">Image source: Bob Books UK<\/span><\/span><\/p><pre>&nbsp;<\/pre><h6>&nbsp;<\/h6><h4><span style=\"color: #000000\"><strong>4. Color<\/strong><\/span><\/h4><h6>&nbsp;<\/h6><p><span style=\"color: #000000\">Color is defined by 3 attributes: hue, saturation, and luminance. These attributes have the power to impact not only the composition of a photograph, but also its mood. Through the strategic manipulation of colors within the frame, you can draw attention to specific areas of the image, or further emphasize particular elements. Additionally, black and white photography can be employed to accentuate contrast, evoke emotions, or underscore essential visual elements in your pictures.<\/span><\/p><p><img src=\"https:\/\/blog.depositphotos.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/12\/Photo-composition-element-color.jpg.webp\" alt=\"photo composition element color\"><span style=\"color: #666666\"><span style=\"font-size: 0.625rem;\">Image source: Bob Books UK<\/span><\/span><\/p><pre>&nbsp;<\/pre><h6>&nbsp;<\/h6><h4><span style=\"color: #000000\"><strong>5. Positive and Negative Space<\/strong><\/span><\/h4><h6>&nbsp;<\/h6><p><span style=\"color: #000000\">The manner in which elements and objects are sized and positioned within the frame can significantly influence how the viewer perceives the image. By skillfully managing spatial relationships in your photos, you have the ability to communicate a particular atmosphere or direct the viewer's attention to a captivating or meaningful aspect of the composition. In photography, the term \"positive space\" often pertains to the subject or filled in areas, where as \"negative space\" often refers to the empty areas of your shot.<\/span><\/p><p><img src=\"https:\/\/blog.depositphotos.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/12\/Photo-composition-element-positive-and-negative-space.jpg.webp\" alt=\"photo composition element positive and negative space\"><\/p><\/div>",
