		"ITEM_DESCRIPTION" : "<div data-bbid=\"bbml-editor-id_8bceb44c-4ed6-4a29-926b-8496343cd7bb\"><p>The word exposure is thrown around a lot in photography. In the old days, people referred to photos themselves as exposures because you exposed film in the camera to light when you took a picture. However today, those terms have grown out of fashion in favor for more modern terms like shots, photos, images, or even files to refer to their photographs.<\/p><p><a href=\"@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav\/xid-18057563_1\" data-bbtype=\"attachment\" data-bbfile=\"{&quot;alternativeText&quot;:&quot; &quot;,&quot;displayName&quot;:&quot; &quot;,&quot;fileName&quot;:&quot;camera_settings.jpg&quot;,&quot;fileSize&quot;:535653,&quot;isDecorative&quot;:true,&quot;mimeType&quot;:&quot;image\/jpeg&quot;,&quot;render&quot;:&quot;inlineOnly&quot;,&quot;resourceUrl&quot;:&quot;@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@sessions\/5A\/5A2590B9C0233C0A62E035DF578C6310\/f77e4c637c454683965e42f9dc9022a8\/camera_settings.jpg&quot;,&quot;linkName&quot;:&quot; &quot;}\"> <\/a><\/p><p>Exposure however still remains as a fundamental cornerstone of photography, and as you set the camera up to take photos, it's essential that you keep track of these three exposure settings: ISO, Shutter Speed, and Aperture.<\/p><pre>&nbsp;<\/pre><p><span style=\"font-size: 1.125rem;\"><strong><span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">ISO, Shutter Speed, and Aperture<\/span><\/strong><\/span><\/p><p>Otherwise known as&nbsp;<strong>The Exposure Triangle<\/strong>, these three camera and lens controls work together to regulate the amount of light that makes it to the light-sensitive surface of your camera (aperture and shutter speed) and the sensitivity of that surface (digital ISO).<\/p><br><p><img src=\"https:\/\/static.bhphotovideo.com\/explora\/sites\/default\/files\/styles\/960\/public\/01-the-exposure-triangle-aperture-iso-shutter.png?itok=n64ws_n1\"><\/p><p><span style=\"color: #666666\"><span style=\"font-size: 0.625rem;\">Image Source: Vorenkamp, T. (2022).&nbsp;<\/span><\/span><span style=\"color: #666666\"><span style=\"font-size: 0.625rem;\"><em>Understanding Exposure, Part 1: The Exposure Triangle<\/em><\/span><\/span><\/p><p>Each of these three settings adjusts how bright your photo is, but they do it in their own unique ways. In other words, each brings it's own \"side effects\" to an image, making it a bit of an art to find the right balance among all three to achieve a desired visual outcome.<\/p><p>Let's take a closer look at each setting individually to gain a clearer understanding of their varying functions and effects.<\/p><br><p><span style=\"font-family: Open Sans;\"><span style=\"font-size: 1.125rem;\"><strong>Aperture:<\/strong><\/span><\/span><\/p><p>The opening in every lens that lets light into the camera is called the aperture. The aperture plays an important part in exposure, and it‚Äôs value on a camera's settings is expressed as an f-number. Apertures shrink and grow by means of a mechanical iris, so when the aperture widens (smaller f-number), more light is permitted to enter; conversely, a narrower aperture (larger f-number) permits less light into the lens.<\/p><p><a href=\"http:\/\/3.bp.blogspot.com\/-iNHvdseuWOk\/UZw3hvEGAGI\/AAAAAAAAAWg\/UzowPjW7DtA\/s1600\/changing-aperture-flower.png\" data-bbtype=\"image\" data-bbfile=\"{&quot;alt&quot;:&quot;&quot;}\">http:\/\/3.bp.blogspot.com\/-iNHvdseuWOk\/UZw3hvEGAGI\/AAAAAAAAAWg\/UzowPjW7DtA\/s1600\/changing-aperture-flower.png<\/a><\/p><p>Beyond just the image's exposure, this mechanism also influences how much of the photo appears in sharp focus, otherwise known as the&nbsp;<strong>depth of field&nbsp;<\/strong>(as shown above). This allows for creative control over the background blur and subject emphasis. A wider aperture produces a shallower depth of field, blurring the background and emphasizing the subject. Conversely, a narrower aperture creates a larger depth of field, keeping more of the scene in focus from foreground to background.&nbsp;<\/p><br><p><span style=\"font-family: Open Sans;\"><span style=\"font-size: 1.125rem;\"><strong>Shutter Speed:<\/strong><\/span><\/span><\/p><p><span style=\"font-family: Open Sans;\">Shutter speeds in digital photography control how long the camera's sensor is exposed to light, affecting both the exposure and motion in photos. Think of it as a window that opens and closes within the camera, allowing light to hit the sensor.<\/span><\/p><p><a href=\"@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav\/xid-18058126_1\" data-bbtype=\"attachment\" data-bbfile=\"{&quot;alternativeText&quot;:&quot; &quot;,&quot;displayName&quot;:&quot; &quot;,&quot;fileName&quot;:&quot;2_Its-a-matter-of-balance-with-exposures.jpg&quot;,&quot;fileSize&quot;:266433,&quot;isDecorative&quot;:true,&quot;mimeType&quot;:&quot;image\/jpeg&quot;,&quot;render&quot;:&quot;inlineOnly&quot;,&quot;resourceUrl&quot;:&quot;@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@sessions\/5A\/5A2590B9C0233C0A62E035DF578C6310\/46379f88532c459bb44fa2f9c78ea93e\/2_Its-a-matter-of-balance-with-exposures.jpg&quot;,&quot;linkName&quot;:&quot; &quot;}\"> <\/a><span style=\"font-family: Open Sans;\">When you opt for faster shutter speeds, you essentially reduce the time the sensor is exposed to light. This has the effect of freezing fast-moving subjects or actions in your frame, essentially limiting the amount of movement or motion blur present in your image (as shown on the left). Conversely, slower shutter speeds extend the duration of exposure, allowing the camera's sensor to soak in more light. This results in much more prominent motion blur in the photo (as shown on the right), which is often used as a creative tool for certain styles of photography.<\/span><\/p><br><p><span style=\"font-family: Open Sans;\"><span style=\"font-size: 1.125rem;\"><strong>ISO:<\/strong><\/span><\/span><\/p><p>ISO, also referred to as the ISO sensitivity or ISO speed,&nbsp;is the term used to characterize the strength of the signal coming out of a camera‚Äôs image sensor.&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: Open Sans;\">The ISO determines the sensitivity of the camera's image sensor to light, and it essentially controls how bright or dark an image appears in different lighting conditions.<\/span><\/p><p><a href=\"@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav\/xid-18057590_1\" data-bbtype=\"attachment\" data-bbfile=\"{&quot;alternativeText&quot;:&quot; &quot;,&quot;displayName&quot;:&quot; &quot;,&quot;fileName&quot;:&quot;ISO-brightness-chart.jpg.png&quot;,&quot;fileSize&quot;:1879262,&quot;isDecorative&quot;:true,&quot;mimeType&quot;:&quot;image\/png&quot;,&quot;render&quot;:&quot;inlineOnly&quot;,&quot;resourceUrl&quot;:&quot;@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@sessions\/5A\/5A2590B9C0233C0A62E035DF578C6310\/820d4aed3e664024807980b4842999d5\/ISO-brightness-chart.jpg.png&quot;,&quot;linkName&quot;:&quot; &quot;}\"> <\/a><\/p><p><span style=\"font-family: Open Sans;\">As shown above, a higher ISO value makes the camera sensor more sensitive, often resulting in brighter images, but potentially introducing digital noise into the shot. Lower ISO values on the other hand produce darker images, but introduce much less noise.<\/span><\/p><pre> <\/pre><p><span style=\"font-size: 1.125rem;\"><strong>Activity Time!<\/strong><\/span><\/p><p>I'm confident you've now got a good grasp of the basics and fundamentals of the exposure triangle from the information shared above! If you're feeling extra curious and want to dive deeper into this topic, I've put together some extra resources for your in this week's folder. Feel free to check them out!&nbsp;<span style=\"color: #333333\">üòÑ<\/span><\/p><p>Now, let's put your newfound knowledge to the test, shall we? Go ahead and kick off your learning journey by participating in our very first course activity!&nbsp;You can find it&nbsp;<a href=\"@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@ultra\/courses\/_13995_1\/outline\/assessment\/test\/_849099_1?courseId=_13995_1&amp;gradeitemView=details\">here.<\/a><\/p><p>Looking forward to seeing your outputs!&nbsp;<\/p><\/div>",
