		"ITEM_NAME" : "Consistency",
		"ITEM_DESCRIPTION" : "<p style=\"text-align: justify;margin: 0.0in 0.0in 8.0pt;line-height: 107.0%;font-size: 11.0pt;font-family: Calibri , sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt;line-height: 107.0%;font-family: Arial , sans-serif;\">This quote reveals an important nature of life itself. I believe that it has something to do with the habit of consistency. When one separates from consistency, even for one moment, it has the potential of destroying that which you care for the most. For example, a lifetime of trust with another person can be ruined by a single moment of betrayal. One can try to repair a broken trust, yet it will not be as great as it was before. The quote further amplifies the consequences of deviating from consistency by using the words ‚Äúthousand‚Äù and ‚Äúfraction‚Äù, both of which are opposite in value. As time is further invested into something meaningful, it only takes a fraction of that time to destroy it. In my own perspective, being consistent is a lifetime habit that rewards those who remain passionate to the things they care about. It also grants the ability of seeing the \"fraction\" of a moment that ruins meaningful things in life.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>",
